    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-02-17T16:53:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-02-17T16:53:00-05:00" n="196"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">315/2–1653: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d196fn1">
                        <p>Drafted by the Director of the Office of <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                                >UN</gloss> Political and Security Affairs (<persName
                                corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1">Wainhouse</persName>); approved for
                            transmission by the Assistant Secretary of State for <gloss
                                target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Affairs (<persName
                                corresp="#p_HICKERSONJD1">Hickerson</persName>); signed by <persName
                                corresp="#p_OCONNORRL1">Roderic L. O’Connor</persName>, Special
                            Assistant to the Secretary of State.</p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1">Lodge</persName> had raised the
                            question of the U.S. position vis-à-vis <persName
                                corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName> against the possibility
                            of an early Security Council meeting on the problem, perhaps on Feb. 20.
                            The United Kingdom seemed to be “pursuing <persName
                                corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName> candidacy on theory that
                                <persName corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName> would be
                            acceptable to <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>.” <persName
                                corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName>’s name would be
                            presented, and there would be an “attempt to get his name recommended
                            without a vote on basis of there being no objection.” <persName
                                corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1">Lodge</persName> concluded, “In my judgment
                            it would be desirable to vote for and not oppose <persName
                                corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName> if issue arises in this
                            way in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>. If we could get agreement on
                            him quickly and expeditiously, I feel that would merit such US support.”
                            (315/2–1653)</p>
                    </note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-02-17T16:53:00-05:00"
                            >February 17, 1953—4:53 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>308. Eyes only <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1">Lodge</persName> from the Secretary. Re <gloss
                        target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 522—<gloss target="#t_SYG1"
                    >SyG</gloss>.</p>
                <p>I share your feeling that we neither oppose nor identify US with <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> initiative on behalf of <persName
                        corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName>. I also share your view that we
                    should vote for <persName corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1">Pearson</persName> if issue
                    arises in <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> and raise no objection to his name
                    if no vote is taken.</p>
                <p>You might indicate to <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> that in event <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> vetoes <persName corresp="#p_PEARSONLB1"
                        >Pearson</persName> candidacy you would hope to have their support for a
                    candidate of our choosing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
